-The `SELECT` expression syntax is as follows:
+## Lexical structure
 
+### Case sensitivity
+
+Keywords are case-sensitive. The control keywords (`SELECT`, `FROM`, `WHERE`, `AND`, `OR`, `NOT`,
+`IN`, `BETWEEN`) are written in UPPER case. The boolean literals `true` and `false` are written in
+lower case. Identifiers (class, bus, session, and property names) preserve the case used in the
+schema definition.
+
+### Keywords (reserved words)
+
+The following words cannot be used as identifiers in a query:
+
+```
+SELECT   FROM    WHERE
+AND      OR      NOT
+IN       BETWEEN
+true     false
+```
+
+### Identifiers
+
+An identifier begins with a letter or underscore and continues with letters, digits, or
+underscores. Identifiers name classes, sessions, buses, and properties.
+
+Two pseudo-properties are always available on every object, regardless of its class:
+
+- `name`: a string, the object's name.
+- `id`: an unsigned integer, the object's identifier.
+
+### String literals
+
+Strings are enclosed in double or single quotes. Both forms are equivalent.
+
+```sql
+"ownship"
+'ownship'
+```
+
+Enumeration values are written as strings using the unqualified value name. For example,
+`"friendly"`, not `"rpr.ForceIdentifierEnum.friendly"`.
+
+### Numeric literals
+
+Integers are written as a non-empty sequence of decimal digits, for example `42`.
+
+Real numbers use a dot as decimal separator and require digits on both sides of the dot. `0.5` is
+valid; `1.` and `.5` are not.
+
+Negative values are not literals. They are produced by applying the unary minus operator to a
+non-negative literal (`- 5`, `-3.14`).
+
+### Boolean literals
+
+`true` and `false`, in lower case.
+
+### Comments and whitespace
+
+Line comments start with `//` and extend to the end of the line. Whitespace (spaces, tabs, carriage
+returns, newlines) separates tokens and is otherwise ignored.
+
+## Grammar
+
+The grammar is given in W3C-style EBNF.
+
+```ebnf
+Query          ::= "SELECT" SelectList "FROM" BusName ( "WHERE" Expression )?
+
+SelectList     ::= "*" | ClassName
+ClassName      ::= Identifier ( "." Identifier )*
+BusName        ::= Identifier "." Identifier
+
+Expression     ::= LogicOr
+LogicOr        ::= LogicAnd  ( "OR"  LogicAnd  )*
+LogicAnd       ::= Equality  ( "AND" Equality  )*
+Equality       ::= Comparison ( ( "=" | "!=" ) Comparison )?
+Comparison     ::= Term ( CompOp Term )?
+                 | Term "NOT"? "BETWEEN" Term "AND" Term
+                 | Term "NOT"? "IN" "(" Term ( "," Term )* ")"
+CompOp         ::= "<" | "<=" | ">" | ">="
+Term           ::= Factor ( ( "+" | "-" ) Factor )*
+Factor         ::= Unary  ( ( "*" | "/" ) Unary  )*
+Unary          ::= ( "!" | "-" | "NOT" ) Unary | Primary
+Primary        ::= Literal | Variable | "(" Expression ")"
+
+Variable       ::= Identifier ( "." Identifier )*
+
+Literal        ::= StringLiteral | IntegerLiteral | RealLiteral | BooleanLiteral
+BooleanLiteral ::= "true" | "false"
+
+Identifier     ::= ( Letter | "_" ) ( Letter | Digit | "_" )*
+StringLiteral  ::= '"' Char* '"' | "'" Char* "'"
+IntegerLiteral ::= Digit+
+RealLiteral    ::= Digit+ "." Digit+
+Letter         ::= [A-Za-z]
+Digit          ::= [0-9]
+```
+
+Notes:
+
+1. `BusName` does not accept wildcards. Both the session and the bus names are mandatory.
+2. Equality (`=`, `!=`) and non-range comparisons (`<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=`) do not chain. `a = b = c`
+   and `a < b < c` are rejected. Use `AND` to combine comparisons: `a = b AND b = c`.
+3. `BETWEEN`, `IN`, `NOT BETWEEN`, and `NOT IN` each act on a single term. Combine them with other
+   conditions using `AND` or `OR`.
+4. The `AND` inside `BETWEEN x AND y` is a structural separator, not a logical conjunction.
+
+### Operator precedence
+
+Listed from lowest to highest. Binary operators associate left-to-right except where noted.
+
+| Level | Operators                                                                   | Notes                  |
+| ----- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------- |
+| 1     | `OR`                                                                        | logical disjunction    |
+| 2     | `AND`                                                                       | logical conjunction    |
+| 3     | `=`, `!=`                                                                   | no chaining            |
+| 4     | `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=`, `BETWEEN ... AND ...`, `IN (...)`, `NOT BETWEEN`, `NOT IN` | no chaining        |
+| 5     | `+`, `-` (binary)                                                           |                        |
+| 6     | `*`, `/`                                                                    |                        |
+| 7     | `!`, unary `-`, `NOT`                                                       | right-associative      |
+| 8     | `.` (path navigation)                                                       | property or name path  |
+
+## Semantics
+
+### SELECT clause
+
+`SELECT ClassName` expresses interest in objects of the given class. The class name may be qualified
+with its package, for example `rpr.PhysicalEntity`. `SELECT *` expresses interest in objects of any
+class.
+
+### FROM clause
+
+`FROM session.bus` names the session and the bus on which to match objects. Both parts are
+mandatory. Wildcards are not accepted.
+
+### WHERE clause
+
+`WHERE` is optional. A query without a `WHERE` clause matches every object of the selected class on
+the selected bus. When present, the condition is evaluated against each candidate object and the
+object is included when the condition is `true`.
+
+Conditions are composed with:
+
+- `AND`: both operands must hold.
+- `OR`: at least one operand must hold.
+- `NOT`: inverts its operand.
+
+### Property paths
+
+A variable refers to a property through a dotted path:
+
+- Top-level property: `focusLevel`.
+- Struct field: `position.x`.
+- Variant alternative: `spatial.SpatialFPStruct.lon`. The first segment is the property name, the
+  next names the variant alternative, and any remaining segments navigate into that alternative's
+  structure.
+- Pseudo-properties: `name` (string) and `id` (unsigned integer).
+
+### Variants
+
+When a variable path targets a specific variant alternative and the variant does not currently hold
+that alternative, the comparison returns `false`. No error is raised.
+
+### Optional properties
+
+An optional property may or may not carry a value. When it does not carry a value, any comparison
+involving it evaluates to `false`. This means `WHERE optionalValue > 5` matches only objects for
+which the property is present and its value is greater than 5.
+
+There is currently no syntax to ask whether an optional is empty or present. An explicit
+`IS NULL` / `IS NOT NULL` form is planned; see [Planned extensions](#planned-extensions).
+
+### Range checks (`BETWEEN`)
+
+`x BETWEEN min AND max` matches when `x` is greater than or equal to `min` and less than or equal
+to `max`. When `min` and `max` are both numeric literals and `min` is greater than `max`, the query
+is rejected at parse time.
+
+### Set membership (`IN`)
+
+`x IN (v1, v2, ..., vn)` matches when `x` equals any of the listed values. The value list must
+contain at least one value.
+
+## More examples
+
+The following queries isolate individual features. Each example is a complete, valid query.
+
+### Any class on a bus
+
+`SELECT *` matches objects of every class published on the bus.
+
+```sql
+SELECT * FROM se.env WHERE isActive = true
+```
+
+### No `WHERE` clause
+
+Omitting `WHERE` matches every object of the class on the bus.
+
+```sql
+SELECT rpr.Aircraft FROM se.env
+```
+
+### Match by id
+
+`id` is a pseudo-property available on every object.
+
+```sql
+SELECT * FROM se.env WHERE id = 42
+```
+
+### Boolean property with `NOT`
+
+A boolean property can be used directly as a condition. `NOT` negates it.
+
+```sql
+SELECT se.Sensor FROM se.env WHERE NOT isFaulty
 ```
-SELECT class_name
